			<div class='cuisine-prompt'>
				<h2 class="h2-heading">Cuisine</h2>
				<p class="p-content"> Cuisine across China varies very much depending on the region.  In fact, there have been classified eight unique regional cuisines with the most influential being Cantanose, Shandong, Jiangsu, and Sichuan. There are however some common staple foods found with many meals.  The one staple you’ll likely find at every meal or used to make a different food product is rice.  Closely behind rice, there are noodles, wheat (bread, buns, noodles), soy products (tofu, soy sauce, soy milk), eggs, and then a huge variety of vegetables as well as meats.  Just to name some of the more common vegetables found there is Chinese eggplant, Chinese mushrooms, Chinese broccoli, leafy vegetables, bamboo shoots, onion, white radishes, and so much more.  Meat and all of its byproducts, be it skin, fat, blood, and even entrails, are also used in many dishes with the choice of meat primarily being pork, beef, chicken and duck. </p>
				<p class="p-content">Chinese cuisine is also known for its wide use of unique spices.  Some of the more common spices used in many of the cuisine include ginger, spring onions, garlic, chilies, anise, cinnamon, peppercorns, as well as many dried spices.  Sauces are also quite common with some of the more popular ones being soy sauce, hoisin sauce, oyster sauce, fish sauce, as well as the many varieties of vinegar which may be used on its own or in a sauce.</p>
			</div>


