				<h2 class="h2-heading">Geography</h2>
				<p class="p-content">Like its cuisine, the geography of China varies much depending on the region.  China’s geography is characterized by its vast mountain ranges, large basins and plateaus, as well as its wide flatlands.  The location of these geographic features can be roughly divided into three regions, the more mountain and plateau dominant area in the southwest third of the country, the desert basins in the northwest third and the flatlands in the eastern third.  Despite the smaller area of the eastern third of the country, nearly ninety-five percent of the country’s population lives in this area.  This is primarily due to the fertile lands that are situated in this region as well as its proximity to the Pacific.</p>
				<p class="p-content">Another important characteristic of China’s vast geography is its rivers which are an important feature in why the country’s flatlands are as fertile as it is.  China is home to two of the longest rivers in the world with the Yangtze River at nearly four thousand miles long and the Yellow River at approximately thirty-four thousand miles long.  These two rivers both run from the western mountain ranges into the eastern flatlands and into the Pacific.  Besides these two major rivers, there are more than 50,000 rivers throughout China.</p>
